{"title_page": "Giuseppe Sala", "text_new": "{{For|the 19th-century Italian cardinal|Giuseppe Antonio Sala}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Giuseppe Sala\n| image               = Giuseppe Sala.jpeg\n| office1             = [[Mayor of Milan]]\n| term_start1         = 21 June 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Giuliano Pisapia]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Expo 2015|CEO of Expo 2015]]\n| term_start2         = June 2010\n| term_end2           = December 2015\n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1958|05|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Milan]], [[Lombardy]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| profession          = Manager, politician\n| alma_mater          = [[Bocconi University]]\n| party               = [[Centre-left coalition|Centre-left]] independent\n}}\n\n'''Giuseppe \"Beppe\" Sala''' (born 28 May 1958) is an Italian manager and politician. He was CEO of the [[Expo 2015|2015 Universal Exposition]] in [[Milan]] from June 2010 to December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ilghirlandaio.com/top-news/78111/expo-2015-giuseppe-sala-nominato-commissario-unico/ |title=Expo 2015, Giuseppe Sala nominato commissario unico |access-date=2016-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030906/http://www.ilghirlandaio.com/top-news/78111/expo-2015-giuseppe-sala-nominato-commissario-unico/ |archive-date=2017-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Afterwards, he was chosen as the [[centre-left coalition]] candidate for [[Mayor of Milan]] in the [[2016 Milan municipal election|2016 municipal election]], which he won, becoming mayor on 21 June 2016.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.it/2016/02/07/primarie-milano-centrosinistra_n_9182860.html Primarie Centrosinistra a Milano. Vince Beppe Sala sulla sinistra disunita]</ref>\n\n==Business career==\n===Expo 2015===\n{{main|Expo 2015}}\n\nIn 2015 [[Milan]] hosted the [[Expo 2015|Universal Exposition]]; the themes were technology, innovation, culture and traditions concerning food.<ref>[http://www.expo2015.org/it/cos-e/il-tema Il Tema \u2013 Expo Milano 2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503132103/http://www.expo2015.org/it/cos-e/il-tema |date=2014-05-03 }}</ref> Participants in the Expo included 145 countries, three international organisations, several civil society organisations, several corporations and [[non-governmental organization]]s (NGOs).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expo2015.org/en/participants |title=Expo2015 Participants |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502064935/http://www.expo2015.org/en/participants |archivedate=2014-05-02 }}</ref> The participants were hosted inside [[Expo 2015 pavilions|individual or grouped pavilions]]. In June 2010 Sala was appointed CEO of the Expo, which led to the nickname \"Mr. Expo\" in the following years.<ref>[http://milano.corriere.it/amministrative-2016/notizie/nella-squadra-mr-expo-spuntano-ambrosoli-linus-3fdacf20-30e2-11e6-9fca-ee7a08dfacf4.shtml Elezioni Comunali Milano 2016: Nella squadra di Mr Expo spuntano Ambrosoli e Linus]</ref>\n\nThe opening of the Expo on 1 May 2015 was marred by protest from anti-austerity activists, [[black bloc]], and anarchists which caused criminal damage, resulting in the police using [[tear gas]].<ref name=indy>{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Michael|title=Milan Expo 2015: Rioting and tear gas mar the start of a 'brighter tomorrow' for Italy|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/milan-expo-2015-rioting-and-tear-gas-mar-the-startof-a-brighter-tomorrow-for-italy-10220036.html|accessdate=1 May 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|date=1 May 2015|location=London}}</ref><ref>https://inhabitat.com/anti-expo-protests-in-milan-erupt-in-violence-clashes-with-riot-police/</ref>\n\nExpo also created some tensions with the [[Holy See]] and the Italian government; in fact [[Pope Francis]] condemned the concept of Expo, saying that it \"obeys the culture of waste and does not contribute to a model of equitable and sustainable development\".<ref name=indy/> As [[Vatican City]] invested \u20ac3 million to obtain its own pavilion at the event before his appointment to the papacy, Francis said that, although it is a good thing that the Church is involved in causes that battle hunger and promote cleaner energy, he stated that too much money was wasted on the Expo itself by Vatican City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Papa Francesco si arrabbia per i soldi spesi dal Vaticano per l\u2019Expo|trans-title=Pope Francis angered by the money spent by the Vatican on the Expo|url=http://www.direttanews.it/2015/04/27/papa-francesco-si-arrabbia-per-i-soldi-spesi-dal-vaticano-per-lexpo/|accessdate=2 May 2015|work=Diretta News|date=27 April 2015|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Mayor of Milan===\n[[File:Sala-Severgnini Barcolana 2016.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Giuseppe Sala with the journalist [[Beppe Severgnini]] in October 2016.]]\nOn 22 March 2015, the incumbent mayor of Milan, [[Giuliano Pisapia]], announced that he had chosen not to run for re-election in 2016 for a second term in office. Following Pisapia's decision, the ruling center-left coalition decided to call an [[primary election|open primary election]] to choose a new single mayoral candidate.<ref>{{cite news|title= Milano, il centrosinistra ha deciso: primarie il 7 febbraio.|url=http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/12/08/news/primarie_centrosinistra_milano-129055040/ |author=Oriana Liso|date=December 8, 2015|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=December 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSala and three other people registered to be candidates in this election.<ref>{{cite news|title= Milano, Giuseppe Sala ai blocchi di partenza.|url=http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/12/22/news/elezioni_milano_sala-129969533/ |author=Oriana Liso|date=December 22, 2015|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> The other candidates were Francesca Balzani, the then deputy mayor of Milan, responsible for the Budget in [[Milan]]'s municipal government and a former [[Member of the European Parliament]];<ref>{{cite news|title= Milano, la vicesindaco Balzani si candida.|url=http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/12/17/news/francesca_balzani_entro_domenica_la_vicesindaco_annuncera_la_candidatura_alle_primarie_pd_confronto_con_sel_sala_-129642954/ |author=Oriana Liso|date=December 16, 2015|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> Pierfrancesco Majorino, then responsible for Social Equalities in the municipal government of Milan;<ref>{{cite news|title= Primarie Milano, Majorini ce l'ha fatta.|url= http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/12/22/news/majorino-130001136/|author=Oriana Liso|date=December 22, 2015|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> and Antonio Iannetta, the former president of UISP.\n\nThe election took place on 6\u20137 February 2016 and Sala won with 25,600 and 42.3% of the vote.<ref>[http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/notizie/2016-02-07/primarie-milano-buona-l-affluenza-grillo-polemizza-voti-cinesi--172340.shtml?uuid=ACY3QaPC Beppe Sala vince le primarie di Milano]</ref>\n\nOn 5 June, in the first round of the [[2016 Milan municipal election|municipal election]] Sala gained 41.7% of first votes; on 19 June, in the second round, he defeated the centre-right candidate [[Stefano Parisi]] with 51.7% against 48.3%.<ref>[http://tg24.sky.it/tg24/politica/2016/06/20/Ballottaggio-milano-comunali-vittoria-sala-sconfitto-parisi.html Milano, vince Sala: \"Lavoreremo con spirito ambrosiano\"]</ref>\n\nOn 16 December 2016 Sala suspended himself from office after learning that he was named in an investigation regarding the Expo 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ansa.it/english/news/politics/2016/12/16/sala-to-suspend-self-over-expo-probe_a8f36320-234f-4d85-aa26-f010f66f1fce.html |title=Sala to suspend self over Expo probe |publisher=Ansa |date=16 December 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/world/2016/12/16/milan-mayor-suspends-himself-over-judicial-probe/ |title=Milan mayor suspends himself over judicial probe |publisher=The Star |date=16 December 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref> He then retired that suspension a few days later.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Giuliano Pisapia]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Milan]]|years=2016\u2013}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Mayors of Milan}}\n{{ItalyMetropolitanMayors}}\n{{ItalyRegionalCapitalMayors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sala, Giuseppe}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Italy) politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian politicians]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Milan]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the 19th-century Italian cardinal|Giuseppe Antonio Sala}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Giuseppe Sala\n| image               = Giuseppe Sala.jpeg\n| office1             = [[Mayor of Milan]]\n| term_start1         = 21 June 2016\n| term_end1           = \n| predecessor1        = [[Giuliano Pisapia]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Expo 2015|CEO of Expo 2015]]\n| term_start2         = June 2010\n| term_end2           = December 2015\n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1958|05|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Milan]], [[Lombardy]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| profession          = Manager, politician\n| alma_mater          = [[Bocconi University]]\n| party               = [[Centre-left coalition|Centre-left]] independent\n}}\n\n'''Giuseppe \"Beppe\" Sala''' (born 28 May 1958) is an Italian manager and politician. He was CEO of the [[Expo 2015|2015 Universal Exposition]] in [[Milan]] from June 2010 to December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ilghirlandaio.com/top-news/78111/expo-2015-giuseppe-sala-nominato-commissario-unico/ |title=Expo 2015, Giuseppe Sala nominato commissario unico |access-date=2016-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030906/http://www.ilghirlandaio.com/top-news/78111/expo-2015-giuseppe-sala-nominato-commissario-unico/ |archive-date=2017-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Sala was also a candidate for the [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]] to become [[Mayor of Milan]] in the [[2016 Milan municipal election|2016 municipal election]], which he won, becoming mayor on 21 June 2016.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.it/2016/02/07/primarie-milano-centrosinistra_n_9182860.html Primarie Centrosinistra a Milano. Vince Beppe Sala sulla sinistra disunita]</ref> Sala is often nicknamed \"Mr. Expo\", for his position as CEO of the Universal Exposition.<ref>[http://milano.corriere.it/amministrative-2016/notizie/nella-squadra-mr-expo-spuntano-ambrosoli-linus-3fdacf20-30e2-11e6-9fca-ee7a08dfacf4.shtml Elezioni Comunali Milano 2016: Nella squadra di Mr Expo spuntano Ambrosoli e Linus]</ref>\n\n==Business career==\n===Expo 2015===\n{{main|Expo 2015}}\n\nIn 2015 [[Milan]] hosted the [[Expo 2015|Universal Exposition]]; the themes were technology, innovation, culture and traditions concerning food.<ref>[http://www.expo2015.org/it/cos-e/il-tema Il Tema \u2013 Expo Milano 2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503132103/http://www.expo2015.org/it/cos-e/il-tema |date=2014-05-03 }}</ref> Participants in the Expo included 145 countries, three international organisations, several civil society organisations, several corporations and [[non-governmental organization]]s (NGOs).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expo2015.org/en/participants |title=Expo2015 Participants |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502064935/http://www.expo2015.org/en/participants |archivedate=2014-05-02 }}</ref> The participants were hosted inside [[Expo 2015 pavilions|individual or grouped pavilions]]. In June 2010 Sala was appointed CEO of the Expo.\n\nThe opening of the Expo on 1 May 2015 was marred by protest from anti-austerity activists, [[black bloc]], and anarchists which caused criminal damage, resulting in the police using [[tear gas]].<ref name=indy>{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Michael|title=Milan Expo 2015: Rioting and tear gas mar the start of a 'brighter tomorrow' for Italy|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/milan-expo-2015-rioting-and-tear-gas-mar-the-startof-a-brighter-tomorrow-for-italy-10220036.html|accessdate=1 May 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|date=1 May 2015|location=London}}</ref><ref>https://inhabitat.com/anti-expo-protests-in-milan-erupt-in-violence-clashes-with-riot-police/</ref>\n\nExpo also created some tensions with the [[Holy See]] and the Italian government; in fact [[Pope Francis]] condemned the concept of Expo, saying that it \"obeys the culture of waste and does not contribute to a model of equitable and sustainable development\".<ref name=indy/> As [[Vatican City]] invested \u20ac3 million to obtain its own pavilion at the event before his appointment to the papacy, Francis said that, although it is a good thing that the Church is involved in causes that battle hunger and promote cleaner energy, he stated that too much money was wasted on the Expo itself by Vatican City.<ref>{{cite news|title=Papa Francesco si arrabbia per i soldi spesi dal Vaticano per l\u2019Expo|trans-title=Pope Francis angered by the money spent by the Vatican on the Expo|url=http://www.direttanews.it/2015/04/27/papa-francesco-si-arrabbia-per-i-soldi-spesi-dal-vaticano-per-lexpo/|accessdate=2 May 2015|work=Diretta News|date=27 April 2015|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===Mayor of Milan===\n[[File:Sala-Severgnini Barcolana 2016.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Giuseppe Sala with the journalist [[Beppe Severgnini]] in October 2016.]]\nOn 22 March 2015, the incumbent mayor of Milan, [[Giuliano Pisapia]], announced that he had chosen not to run for re-election in 2016 for a second term in office. Following Pisapia's decision, the ruling center-left coalition decided to call an [[primary election|open primary election]] to choose a new single mayoral candidate.<ref>{{cite news|title= Milano, il centrosinistra ha deciso: primarie il 7 febbraio.|url=http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/12/08/news/primarie_centrosinistra_milano-129055040/ |author=Oriana Liso|date=December 8, 2015|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=December 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSala and three other people registered to be candidates in this election.<ref>{{cite news|title= Milano, Giuseppe Sala ai blocchi di partenza.|url=http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/12/22/news/elezioni_milano_sala-129969533/ |author=Oriana Liso|date=December 22, 2015|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> The other candidates were Francesca Balzani, the then deputy mayor of Milan, responsible for the Budget in [[Milan]]'s municipal government and a former [[Member of the European Parliament]];<ref>{{cite news|title= Milano, la vicesindaco Balzani si candida.|url=http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/12/17/news/francesca_balzani_entro_domenica_la_vicesindaco_annuncera_la_candidatura_alle_primarie_pd_confronto_con_sel_sala_-129642954/ |author=Oriana Liso|date=December 16, 2015|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> Pierfrancesco Majorino, then responsible for Social Equalities in the municipal government of Milan;<ref>{{cite news|title= Primarie Milano, Majorini ce l'ha fatta.|url= http://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2015/12/22/news/majorino-130001136/|author=Oriana Liso|date=December 22, 2015|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref> and Antonio Iannetta, the former president of UISP.\n\nThe election took place on 6\u20137 February 2016 and Sala won with 25,600 and 42.3% of the vote.<ref>[http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/notizie/2016-02-07/primarie-milano-buona-l-affluenza-grillo-polemizza-voti-cinesi--172340.shtml?uuid=ACY3QaPC Beppe Sala vince le primarie di Milano]</ref>\n\nOn 5 June, in the first round of the [[2016 Milan municipal election|municipal election]] Sala gained 41.7% of first votes; on 19 June, in the second round, he defeated the centre-right candidate [[Stefano Parisi]] with 51.7% against 48.3%.<ref>[http://tg24.sky.it/tg24/politica/2016/06/20/Ballottaggio-milano-comunali-vittoria-sala-sconfitto-parisi.html Milano, vince Sala: \"Lavoreremo con spirito ambrosiano\"]</ref>\n\nOn 16 December 2016 Sala suspended himself from office after learning that he was named in an investigation regarding the Expo 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ansa.it/english/news/politics/2016/12/16/sala-to-suspend-self-over-expo-probe_a8f36320-234f-4d85-aa26-f010f66f1fce.html |title=Sala to suspend self over Expo probe |publisher=Ansa |date=16 December 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/world/2016/12/16/milan-mayor-suspends-himself-over-judicial-probe/ |title=Milan mayor suspends himself over judicial probe |publisher=The Star |date=16 December 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref> He then retired that suspension a few days later.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Giuliano Pisapia]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Milan]]|years=2016\u2013}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Mayors of Milan}}\n{{ItalyMetropolitanMayors}}\n{{ItalyRegionalCapitalMayors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sala, Giuseppe}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Italy) politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Italian politicians]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Milan]]\n", "name_user": "Mssddmit", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giuseppe_Sala"}
{"title_page": "Marwari people", "text_new": "{{short description|Ethnic group that originated from Rajasthan, India}}\n{{Other uses|Marwari (disambiguation){{!}}Marwari}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Marwari\n| flag = <!-- (image filename) -->\n| flag_caption = \n| image = Marwadi Husband and Wife in Traditional Attire Rajasthan India.jpg\n| image_caption = Marwari husband and wife in traditional attire\n| population = \n| genealogy = \n| regions = \n| region1 = India\n| pop1 = Spread across parts of India and mainly in [[Rajasthan]]\n| region2 = Nepal\n| pop2 = 51,443<ref name=\"cbs\">{{Cite web|url=https://unstats.un.org/unsD/demographic/sources/census/wphc/Nepal/Nepal-Census-2011-Vol1.pdf|title=Nepal Census 2011}}</ref> [[Terai]] region and [[Kathmandu Valley]]\n| ref2 =<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofindia.com/world/rest-of-world/Living-in-dread-Marwaris-start-fleeing-Nepal/articleshow/1916984.cms|title=Marwari peoples starts fleeing Nepal |work=The Times of India |date=17 April 2007 |accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref>\n| region3 = \n| pop3 = \n| ref3 = \n| languages = [[Marwari language|Marwari]], [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| religions =Majority: [[Hinduism]], [[Jainism]]<br>Minority: [[Islam]], [[Christianity]]\n| related_groups = [[Rajasthani people]]\n| footnotes = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\nThe '''Marwari''' or '''Marwadi''' are an [[India]]n ethnic group that originate from the [[Rajasthan]] region of India. Their language, also called [[Marwari language|Marwari]], comes under the umbrella of [[Rajasthani language]]s, which is part of the Western Zone of [[Indo-Aryan languages]].\n\nThey have been a highly successful business community, first as inland traders during the era of [[Rajput kingdoms]], and later also as investors in industrial production and other sectors. Today, they control many of the country's largest media groups. Although spread throughout India, historically they have been most concentrated in [[Kolkata]], [[Mumbai]], [[Chennai]], [[Delhi]], [[Nagpur]] and the hinterlands of central and eastern India.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term ''Marwari'' once referred to the area encompassed by the former [[princely state]] of [[Marwar]], also called the [[Jodhpur]] region of southwest Rajasthan in India. It has evolved to be a designation for the [[Rajasthani people]] in general but it is used particularly with reference to certain [[j\u0101ti]]s that fall within the [[Bania (caste)|Bania]] community.  The most prominent among these communities, are the [[Agarwal|Agrawal]]s, [[Khandelwal Vaishya|Khandelwals]], [[Maheshwari]]s and [[Oswal]]s.<ref name=Kudaisya2009p87>{{cite book |chapter=Marwari and Chettiar Merchants. 1850s-1950s: Comparative Trajectories |first=Medha M. |last=Kudaisya |title=Chinese and Indian Business: Historical Antecedents |editor1-first=Medha M. |editor1-last=Kudaisya |editor2-first=Chin-Keong |editor2-last=Ng |publisher=BRILL |location=Leiden |year=2009 |isbn=978-90-04-17279-1 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQJfjnWly5wC&pg=PA87 |page=87 |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref> That said, most people now considered to be of the Marwari community actually have their origins in the districts of [[Jhunjhunu]], [[Churu]] and [[Shekhawati]] rather than Jodhpur; it is possible that the association of the ''Marwari'' term with Jodhpur owes more to the high status of that place in pre-independence India.<ref name=\"hardgrove\"/>\n\nDwijendra Tripathi believes that the term ''Marwari'' was probably used by the traders only when they were outside their home region; that is, by the diaspora.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=From Community to Class: The Marwaris in a Historical Perspective |first=Dwijendra |last=Tripathi |title=Facets of a Marwar Historian |editor1-first=B. L. |editor1-last=Bhandani |editor2-first=Dwijendra |editor2-last=Tripathi |location=Jaipur |publisher=Publication Scheme |year=1996 |pages=189\u2013196 |isbn=978-81-86782-18-7}}</ref> Anne Hardgrove also supports this argument, saying that the Marwari identity could only exist in the context of a diaspora who came ''from'' somewhere and that until they migrated they had no such designation.<ref name=\"hardgrove\">{{cite journal |title=Sati Worship and Marwari Public Identity in India |first=Anne |last=Hardgrove |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |volume=58 |issue=3 |date=August 1999 |pages=723\u2013752 |jstor=2659117|doi=10.2307/2659117 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early origins===\nMarwari traders have historically been migratory in habit. The possible causes of this trait include the proximity of their homeland to the major [Ganges]-[Yamuna] trade route; movement to escape famine; and the encouragement given to them by various rulers of northern India who saw advantages in having their skills in banking and finance.<ref name=Kudaisya2009p87/>\n\nThe pattern of Marwari migration became increasingly divergent following the decline in wars between Rajput kingdoms, which the Marwaris had helped to finance, and the decreasing influence of the community over the North Indian caravan trading routes that resulted from the British establishing themselves in the region. The changed focus of migration was also encouraged by the British establishment of new trading routes and centres, as well as by the declining political significance of the Rajput courts whose famed conspicuous consumption had been supported by Marwari money. The community welcomed the relative safety that the British presence offered, as well as the commercial and legal frameworks that they provided and which were more favourable to Marwari activities than the systems prevalent during the earlier period of [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] and Rajput rule.<ref name=Kudaisya2009p88>{{cite book |chapter=Marwari and Chettiar Merchants. 1850s-1950s: Comparative Trajectories |first=Medha M. |last=Kudaisya |title=Chinese and Indian Business: Historical Antecedents |editor1-first=Medha M. |editor1-last=Kudaisya |editor2-first=Chin-Keong |editor2-last=Ng |publisher=BRILL |location=Leiden |year=2009 |isbn=978-90-04-17279-1 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQJfjnWly5wC&pg=PA88 |page=88 |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Marwari [[Jagat Seth]] family served as bankers to the [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]].\n\n===British era===\nAfter the decline of Mughal authority in Bengal, Marwari traders, bankers and financiers migrated to the growing British power in Calcutta.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rcNdAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA197|title=Commodifying Everything : Relationships of the Market.|last=Strasser|first=Susan|year=2013|publisher=Taylor and Francis|isbn=978-1-13670-685-1|location=Hoboken|page=197}}</ref> There were particularly significant population shifts to [[Mumbai|Bombay]] between 1835-1850 and Kolkata from the 1870s, as well as to [[Chennai|Madras]].<ref name=Kudaisya2009p88/> They continued to spread into areas of British control throughout the nineteenth century, becoming established as ''sahukars'' (moneylenders) and inland trade-brokers in central India and Maharashtra. The migration of these traders accelerated in the second half of the nineteenth century which led to growing unpopularity, and acts of communal violence against them.{{cn|date=January 2018}}\n\nHistorian Medha M. Kudaisya has said that the Marwaris:\n{{quote|made the transition from being niche players in trading to becoming industrial conglomerates&nbsp;... From being brokers and bankers, the Marwaris went on to break the British monopoly over the jute industry after World War I; they then moved into other industrial sectors, such as cotton and sugar, and set up diversified conglomerates. By the 1950s, the Marwaris dominated the India private industry scenario, emerging as the establishers of its most prominent business houses.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Marwari and Chettiar Merchants. 1850s-1950s: Comparative Trajectories |first=Medha M. |last=Kudaisya |title=Chinese and Indian Business: Historical Antecedents |editor1-first=Medha M. |editor1-last=Kudaisya |editor2-first=Chin-Keong |editor2-last=Ng |publisher=BRILL |location=Leiden |year=2009 |isbn=978-90-04-17279-1 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQJfjnWly5wC&pg=PA86 |page=86 |accessdate=2012-05-23}}</ref>}}\n\nA considerable number of Marwari business groups made their fortune on speculative markets in the nineteenth and early twentieth century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5cWUAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT56|title=The Marwaris: from Jagat Seth to the Birlas|last=Timberg|first=Thomas A.|publisher=Portfolio Penguin|year=2014|isbn=978-0-14342-405-5|location=New Delhi|page=56}}</ref>\n\nAlthough maintaining close and public ties with the British authorities, members of the Marwari business community where early financial supporters of the [[History of the Indian National Congress|Indian National Congress]], often in secret.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Independent India===\nIn 1956, the All-India Marwari Federation opposed a linguistic organisation of states whilst buying up regional language newspapers in Maharashtra, Tamil Nadu and Andhra Pradesh.<ref>''The Times of India'', 11 February 1956, p. 3.</ref> Today, they control many of the country's largest media groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/article/marwari-power/indian-media-marwaris-write-the-script/37361/1|title=Indian Media: Marwaris Write the Script {{!}} Forbes India|last=Ajwani|first=Deepak|date=18 March 2014|website=Forbes India|language=en-US|access-date=25 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe community's control of the Indian economy declined following the country's 1991 economic reforms. From a peak of controlling 24 per cent in 1990, it had fallen to less than 2 per cent in 2000, apparently because of an unwillingness to adapt. The 2000 figure is considered to be lower than the position in 1939, when the community first began its resurgence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Marwaris-losing-business-acumen/articleshow/9005397.cms|title=Marwaris losing business acumen|last=Niyogi|first=Subhro|date=6 May 2002|work=The Times of India|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Language==\nMarwari, or Marrubhasha, as it is referred to by Marwaris, is the traditional, historical, language of the Marwari ethnicity. The Marwari language is closely related to the Rajasthani language. The latter evolved from the [[Old Gujarati language|Old Gujarati]] (also called ''Old Western Rajasthani'', ''Gujjar Bhakha'' or ''Maru-Gurjar''), language spoken by the people in [[Gujarat]] and Rajasthan.<ref>{{cite book|title=Revealing India's past: recent trends in art and archaeology|author=Ajay Mitra Shastri|author2=R. K. Sharma|author3=Devendra Handa|publisher=Aryan Books International|year=2005|isbn=978-81-7305-287-3|page=227|quote=It is an established fact that during 10th-11th century&nbsp;... Interestingly the language was known as the Gujjar Bhakha.}}</ref> It has been noted that throughout the state of Rajasthan, people avoid identifying their language by name, preferring to identify themselves as speaking \"Rajasthani\" with Marwari literature and taught as Rajasthani until secondary level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-documents/lsi/lsi_Rajasthan/5_Marwari.pdf|title=Marwari|last=Mukherjee|first=Kakali|date=2011|website=Census India|page=35}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\nMarwaris have been known for a tightly-knit social solidarity, described by [[Selig Harrison]] in 1960 as \"indissoluble under the impact of the strongest regional solvents\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9jbWCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA116|title=India: the most dangerous decades.|last=Harrison|first=Selig, S.|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1960|isbn=978-1-40087-780-5|page=116}}</ref> The perception held of their culture by other communities is ambivalent at best. Hardgrove notes that they are \"known across India for their success in business and industry , and often despised and severely criticised by other Indians for their alleged corruption and social conservatism\". The latter aspect is particularly evident in the status of women within the Marwari community: it is probably correct that, generally speaking, they are less educated than those of even other wealthy communities and if they have any form of further education it tends not to be with the aim of pursuing a career but rather of enhancing domestic life. She says that \"The main duty for Marwari women, it would seem, is to provide a stable household life for their husbands, sons and brothers-in-law\", although she acknowledges that some such women have in recent years been attempting to carve out roles in the wider world through engagement in charitable ventures and even running their own businesses.<ref name=\"hardgrove\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n<!--Arranged alphabetically as per surname-->\n*[[Nidhhi Agerwal]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Nidhhi Agerwal: I am a Tollywood buff who grew up watching Telugu films dubbed in Hindi - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/nidhhi-agerwal-i-am-a-tollywood-buff-who-grew-up-watching-telugu-films-dubbed-in-hindi/articleshow/61660243.cms |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Janaki Devi Bajaj]]<ref name=\"MarwariHeritage\"/>\n*[[Rahul Bajaj]]<ref name=\"MarwariHeritage\"/>\n*[[Shobhana Bhartia]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jain |first1=Gunjan |title=Shobhana Bhartia: (Penguin Petit) |date=2018 |publisher=Penguin Random House India Private Limited |isbn=9789353054175 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=voJ8DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT34&lpg=PT34&dq=shobhana+bhartia+marwari#v=onepage&q=shobhana%20bhartia%20marwari&f=false |accessdate=12 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Kumar Mangalam Birla]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The story of the first couple of the Birla empire |url=https://www.rediff.com/money/slide-show/slide-show-1-the-story-of-the-first-couple-of-the-birla-empire/20110706.htm |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=Rediff |date=6 June 2011 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Jagmohan Dalmiya]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Choudhury |first1=Angikaar |title=Jagmohan Dalmiya (1940-2015): The man who symbolised India's clout in world cricket |url=https://scroll.in/field/756893/jagmohan-dalmiya-1940-2015-the-man-who-symbolised-india-s-clout-in-world-cricket |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Ritu Dalmia]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dalmia |first1=Ritu |title=My freedom to love: 'I was 23 when I realised I was gay. I told my parents. The next day they sent a box of mangoes for my partner at the time' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/independence-day-special/story/20160822-ritu-dalmia-my-freedom-to-love-article-377-lgbt-gay-rights-829406-2016-08-12 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=India Today |date=12 August 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[S. N. Goenka]]<ref>{{cite news |title=You have to work out your own salvation - Indian Express |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/-you-have-to-work-out-your-own-salvation-/640972/0 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=archive.indianexpress.com |date=3 July 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Abhishek Jain]]<ref name=\"SadWeekly 2015\">{{cite web |title='\u0a95\u0ac7\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0ab0\u0ac0\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0a9c\u0a88\u0ab6' \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 '\u0aac\u0ac7 \u0aaf\u0abe\u0ab0'\u0aa8\u0abe \u0ab8\u0ab0\u0acd\u0a9c\u0a95 \u0a85\u0aad\u0abf\u0ab7\u0ac7\u0a95 \u0a9c\u0ac8\u0aa8 \u0a95\u0ab9\u0ac7 \u0a9b\u0ac7...\u0a8f \u0a98\u0a9f\u0aa8\u0abe\u0a8f \u0a9c \u0aae\u0abe\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0aab\u0abf\u0ab2\u0acd\u0aae \u0aac\u0aa8\u0abe\u0ab5\u0ab5\u0abe\u0aa8\u0ac0 \u0aa7\u0a97\u0ab6\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0ab5\u0aa7\u0ac1 \u0aaa\u0acd\u0ab0\u0a97\u0a9f\u0abe\u0ab5\u0ac0| url=http://www.sadhanaweekly.com/article.php?catid=171&issue_date=2015-05-02 | language=gu | date=2 May 2015|accessdate=January 30, 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924093349/http://www.sadhanaweekly.com/article.php?catid=171&issue_date=2015-05-02 |archivedate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Shyamanand Jalan]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Shyamanand Jalan: Eminenet theatre actor Shyamanand Jalan dead {{!}} Kolkata News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Eminenet-theatre-actor-Shyamanand-Jalan-dead/articleshow/5970813.cms |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=25 May 2010 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Rajeev Khandelwal]]<ref>{{cite news |title=rediff.com: Rajeev Khandelwal chats with Rediff Readers |url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jun/11sld4.htm |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=www.rediff.com}}</ref>\n*[[Rohit Khandelwal]]<ref>{{cite news |author=TT Bureau |date=18 September 2016 |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/culture/man-of-the-world/cid/1322667 |title=Man of the world |work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Abhishek Singhvi]]<ref name=\"MarwariHeritage\">{{cite book |last1=Taknet |first1=D. K. |title=The Marwari Heritage |date=2016 |publisher=IntegralDMS |isbn=9781942322061 |page=254 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=kXS2DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA254&lpg=PA254&dq=abhishek+manu+singhvi+marwari#v=onepage&q=singhvi%2C%20birla%2C%20bajaj&f=false |accessdate=12 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Laxmi Mall Singhvi]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Singhvi |first1=Abhishek Manu |last2=Malik |first2=Lokendra |title=India's Vibgyor Man: Selected Writings and Speeches of L.M. Singhvi |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-909407-3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=M_xdDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT35&lpg=PT35&dq=laxmi+mall+singhvi+marwari#v=onepage |accessdate=31 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"MarwariHeritage\"/>\n*[[Liaquat Soldier]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Liaquat 'Soldier' dies of heart attack: Express Tribune |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/140176/liaquat-soldier-dies-of-heart-attack/ |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=teh Express Tribune |date=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tarachand Ghanshyamdas]]\n* [[Marwari Muslims]]\n* [[Karmveer Choudhary]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Marwari people}}\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Marwari people|*]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in India]]\n[[Category:Indo-Aryan peoples]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ethnic group that originated from Rajasthan, India}}\n{{Other uses|Marwari (disambiguation){{!}}Marwari}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Marwari\n| flag = <!-- (image filename) -->\n| flag_caption = \n| image = Marwadi Husband and Wife in Traditional Attire Rajasthan India.jpg\n| image_caption = Marwari husband and wife in traditional attire\n| population = \n| genealogy = \n| regions = \n| region1 = India\n| pop1 = Spread across parts of India and mainly in [[Rajasthan]]\n| region2 = Nepal\n| pop2 = 51,443<ref name=\"cbs\">{{Cite web|url=https://unstats.un.org/unsD/demographic/sources/census/wphc/Nepal/Nepal-Census-2011-Vol1.pdf|title=Nepal Census 2011}}</ref> [[Terai]] region and [[Kathmandu Valley]]\n| ref2 = <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofindia.com/world/rest-of-world/Living-in-dread-Marwaris-start-fleeing-Nepal/articleshow/1916984.cms|title=Marwari peoples starts fleeing Nepal |work=The Times of India |date=17 April 2007 |accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref>\n| region3 = \n| pop3 = \n| ref3 = \n| languages = [[Marwari language|Marwari]], [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| religions =Majority: [[Hinduism]], [[Jainism]]<br>Minority: [[Islam]], [[Christianity]]\n| related_groups = [[Rajasthani people]]\n| footnotes = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\nThe '''Marwari''' or '''Marwadi''' are an [[India]]n ethnic group that originate from the [[Rajasthan]] region of India. Their language, also called [[Marwari language|Marwari]], comes under the umbrella of [[Rajasthani language]]s, which is part of the Western Zone of [[Indo-Aryan languages]].\n\nThey have been a highly successful business community, first as inland traders during the era of [[Rajput kingdoms]], and later also as investors in industrial production and other sectors. Today, they control many of the country's largest media groups. Although spread throughout India, historically they have been most concentrated in [[Kolkata]], [[Mumbai]], [[Chennai]], [[Delhi]], [[Nagpur]] and the hinterlands of central and eastern India.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term ''Marwari'' once referred to the area encompassed by the former [[princely state]] of [[Marwar]], also called the [[Jodhpur]] region of southwest Rajasthan in India. It has evolved to be a designation for the [[Rajasthani people]] in general but it is used particularly with reference to certain [[j\u0101ti]]s that fall within the [[Bania (caste)|Bania]] community.  The most prominent among these communities, are the [[Agarwal|Agrawal]]s, [[Khandelwal Vaishya|Khandelwals]], [[Maheshwari]]s and [[Oswal]]s.<ref name=Kudaisya2009p87>{{cite book |chapter=Marwari and Chettiar Merchants. 1850s-1950s: Comparative Trajectories |first=Medha M. |last=Kudaisya |title=Chinese and Indian Business: Historical Antecedents |editor1-first=Medha M. |editor1-last=Kudaisya |editor2-first=Chin-Keong |editor2-last=Ng |publisher=BRILL |location=Leiden |year=2009 |isbn=978-90-04-17279-1 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQJfjnWly5wC&pg=PA87 |page=87 |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref> That said, most people now considered to be of the Marwari community actually have their origins in the districts of [[Jhunjhunu]], [[Churu]] and [[Shekhawati]] rather than Jodhpur; it is possible that the association of the ''Marwari'' term with Jodhpur owes more to the high status of that place in pre-independence India.<ref name=\"hardgrove\"/>\n\nDwijendra Tripathi believes that the term ''Marwari'' was probably used by the traders only when they were outside their home region; that is, by the diaspora.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=From Community to Class: The Marwaris in a Historical Perspective |first=Dwijendra |last=Tripathi |title=Facets of a Marwar Historian |editor1-first=B. L. |editor1-last=Bhandani |editor2-first=Dwijendra |editor2-last=Tripathi |location=Jaipur |publisher=Publication Scheme |year=1996 |pages=189\u2013196 |isbn=978-81-86782-18-7}}</ref> Anne Hardgrove also supports this argument, saying that the Marwari identity could only exist in the context of a diaspora who came ''from'' somewhere and that until they migrated they had no such designation.<ref name=\"hardgrove\">{{cite journal |title=Sati Worship and Marwari Public Identity in India |first=Anne |last=Hardgrove |journal=The Journal of Asian Studies |volume=58 |issue=3 |date=August 1999 |pages=723\u2013752 |jstor=2659117|doi=10.2307/2659117 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Early origins===\nMarwari traders have historically been migratory in habit. The possible causes of this trait include the proximity of their homeland to the major [Ganges]-[Yamuna] trade route; movement to escape famine; and the encouragement given to them by various rulers of northern India who saw advantages in having their skills in banking and finance.<ref name=Kudaisya2009p87/>\n\nThe pattern of Marwari migration became increasingly divergent following the decline in wars between Rajput kingdoms, which the Marwaris had helped to finance, and the decreasing influence of the community over the North Indian caravan trading routes that resulted from the British establishing themselves in the region. The changed focus of migration was also encouraged by the British establishment of new trading routes and centres, as well as by the declining political significance of the Rajput courts whose famed conspicuous consumption had been supported by Marwari money. The community welcomed the relative safety that the British presence offered, as well as the commercial and legal frameworks that they provided and which were more favourable to Marwari activities than the systems prevalent during the earlier period of [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] and Rajput rule.<ref name=Kudaisya2009p88>{{cite book |chapter=Marwari and Chettiar Merchants. 1850s-1950s: Comparative Trajectories |first=Medha M. |last=Kudaisya |title=Chinese and Indian Business: Historical Antecedents |editor1-first=Medha M. |editor1-last=Kudaisya |editor2-first=Chin-Keong |editor2-last=Ng |publisher=BRILL |location=Leiden |year=2009 |isbn=978-90-04-17279-1 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQJfjnWly5wC&pg=PA88 |page=88 |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Marwari [[Jagat Seth]] family served as bankers to the [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]].\n\n===British era===\nAfter the decline of Mughal authority in Bengal, Marwari traders, bankers and financiers migrated to the growing British power in Calcutta.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rcNdAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA197|title=Commodifying Everything : Relationships of the Market.|last=Strasser|first=Susan|year=2013|publisher=Taylor and Francis|isbn=978-1-13670-685-1|location=Hoboken|page=197}}</ref> There were particularly significant population shifts to [[Mumbai|Bombay]] between 1835-1850 and Kolkata from the 1870s, as well as to [[Chennai|Madras]].<ref name=Kudaisya2009p88/> They continued to spread into areas of British control throughout the nineteenth century, becoming established as ''sahukars'' (moneylenders) and inland trade-brokers in central India and Maharashtra. The migration of these traders accelerated in the second half of the nineteenth century which led to growing unpopularity, and acts of communal violence against them.{{cn|date=January 2018}}\n\nHistorian Medha M. Kudaisya has said that the Marwaris:\n{{quote|made the transition from being niche players in trading to becoming industrial conglomerates&nbsp;... From being brokers and bankers, the Marwaris went on to break the British monopoly over the jute industry after World War I; they then moved into other industrial sectors, such as cotton and sugar, and set up diversified conglomerates. By the 1950s, the Marwaris dominated the India private industry scenario, emerging as the establishers of its most prominent business houses.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Marwari and Chettiar Merchants. 1850s-1950s: Comparative Trajectories |first=Medha M. |last=Kudaisya |title=Chinese and Indian Business: Historical Antecedents |editor1-first=Medha M. |editor1-last=Kudaisya |editor2-first=Chin-Keong |editor2-last=Ng |publisher=BRILL |location=Leiden |year=2009 |isbn=978-90-04-17279-1 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQJfjnWly5wC&pg=PA86 |page=86 |accessdate=2012-05-23}}</ref>}}\n\nA considerable number of Marwari business groups made their fortune on speculative markets in the nineteenth and early twentieth century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5cWUAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT56|title=The Marwaris: from Jagat Seth to the Birlas|last=Timberg|first=Thomas A.|publisher=Portfolio Penguin|year=2014|isbn=978-0-14342-405-5|location=New Delhi|page=56}}</ref>\n\nAlthough maintaining close and public ties with the British authorities, members of the Marwari business community where early financial supporters of the [[History of the Indian National Congress|Indian National Congress]], often in secret.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Independent India===\nIn 1956, the All-India Marwari Federation opposed a linguistic organisation of states whilst buying up regional language newspapers in Maharashtra, Tamil Nadu and Andhra Pradesh.<ref>''The Times of India'', 11 February 1956, p. 3.</ref> Today, they control many of the country's largest media groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/article/marwari-power/indian-media-marwaris-write-the-script/37361/1|title=Indian Media: Marwaris Write the Script {{!}} Forbes India|last=Ajwani|first=Deepak|date=18 March 2014|website=Forbes India|language=en-US|access-date=25 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe community's control of the Indian economy declined following the country's 1991 economic reforms. From a peak of controlling 24 per cent in 1990, it had fallen to less than 2 per cent in 2000, apparently because of an unwillingness to adapt. The 2000 figure is considered to be lower than the position in 1939, when the community first began its resurgence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Marwaris-losing-business-acumen/articleshow/9005397.cms|title=Marwaris losing business acumen|last=Niyogi|first=Subhro|date=6 May 2002|work=The Times of India|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Language==\nMarwari, or Marrubhasha, as it is referred to by Marwaris, is the traditional, historical, language of the Marwari ethnicity. The Marwari language is closely related to the Rajasthani language. The latter evolved from the [[Old Gujarati language|Old Gujarati]] (also called ''Old Western Rajasthani'', ''Gujjar Bhakha'' or ''Maru-Gurjar''), language spoken by the people in [[Gujarat]] and Rajasthan.<ref>{{cite book|title=Revealing India's past: recent trends in art and archaeology|author=Ajay Mitra Shastri|author2=R. K. Sharma|author3=Devendra Handa|publisher=Aryan Books International|year=2005|isbn=978-81-7305-287-3|page=227|quote=It is an established fact that during 10th-11th century&nbsp;... Interestingly the language was known as the Gujjar Bhakha.}}</ref> It has been noted that throughout the state of Rajasthan, people avoid identifying their language by name, preferring to identify themselves as speaking \"Rajasthani\" with Marwari literature and taught as Rajasthani until secondary level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-documents/lsi/lsi_Rajasthan/5_Marwari.pdf|title=Marwari|last=Mukherjee|first=Kakali|date=2011|website=Census India|page=35}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\nMarwaris have been known for a tightly-knit social solidarity, described by [[Selig Harrison]] in 1960 as \"indissoluble under the impact of the strongest regional solvents\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9jbWCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA116|title=India: the most dangerous decades.|last=Harrison|first=Selig, S.|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1960|isbn=978-1-40087-780-5|page=116}}</ref> The perception held of their culture by other communities is ambivalent at best. Hardgrove notes that they are \"known across India for their success in business and industry , and often despised and severely criticised by other Indians for their alleged corruption and social conservatism\". The latter aspect is particularly evident in the status of women within the Marwari community: it is probably correct that, generally speaking, they are less educated than those of even other wealthy communities and if they have any form of further education it tends not to be with the aim of pursuing a career but rather of enhancing domestic life. She says that \"The main duty for Marwari women, it would seem, is to provide a stable household life for their husbands, sons and brothers-in-law\", although she acknowledges that some such women have in recent years been attempting to carve out roles in the wider world through engagement in charitable ventures and even running their own businesses.<ref name=\"hardgrove\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n<!--Arranged alphabetically as per surname-->\n*[[Nidhhi Agerwal]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Nidhhi Agerwal: I am a Tollywood buff who grew up watching Telugu films dubbed in Hindi - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/nidhhi-agerwal-i-am-a-tollywood-buff-who-grew-up-watching-telugu-films-dubbed-in-hindi/articleshow/61660243.cms |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Janaki Devi Bajaj]]<ref name=\"MarwariHeritage\"/>\n*[[Rahul Bajaj]]<ref name=\"MarwariHeritage\"/>\n*[[Shobhana Bhartia]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jain |first1=Gunjan |title=Shobhana Bhartia: (Penguin Petit) |date=2018 |publisher=Penguin Random House India Private Limited |isbn=9789353054175 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=voJ8DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT34&lpg=PT34&dq=shobhana+bhartia+marwari#v=onepage&q=shobhana%20bhartia%20marwari&f=false |accessdate=12 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Kumar Mangalam Birla]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The story of the first couple of the Birla empire |url=https://www.rediff.com/money/slide-show/slide-show-1-the-story-of-the-first-couple-of-the-birla-empire/20110706.htm |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=Rediff |date=6 June 2011 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Jagmohan Dalmiya]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Choudhury |first1=Angikaar |title=Jagmohan Dalmiya (1940-2015): The man who symbolised India's clout in world cricket |url=https://scroll.in/field/756893/jagmohan-dalmiya-1940-2015-the-man-who-symbolised-india-s-clout-in-world-cricket |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=Scroll.in |date=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Ritu Dalmia]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dalmia |first1=Ritu |title=My freedom to love: 'I was 23 when I realised I was gay. I told my parents. The next day they sent a box of mangoes for my partner at the time' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/independence-day-special/story/20160822-ritu-dalmia-my-freedom-to-love-article-377-lgbt-gay-rights-829406-2016-08-12 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=India Today |date=12 August 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[S. N. Goenka]]<ref>{{cite news |title=You have to work out your own salvation - Indian Express |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/-you-have-to-work-out-your-own-salvation-/640972/0 |accessdate=12 November 2019 |work=archive.indianexpress.com |date=3 July 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Abhishek Jain]]<ref name=\"SadWeekly 2015\">{{cite web |title='\u0a95\u0ac7\u0ab5\u0ac0 \u0ab0\u0ac0\u0aa4\u0ac7 \u0a9c\u0a88\u0ab6' \u0a85\u0aa8\u0ac7 '\u0aac\u0ac7 \u0aaf\u0abe\u0ab0'\u0aa8\u0abe \u0ab8\u0ab0\u0ac